Here's a complete example. I'll walk through each file and then explain DI.

---

### Tool Class — `ApiTools.cs`

```csharp
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get a user by ID from the REST API.")]
    public async Task<string> GetUser(
        [Description("The numeric user ID")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching user {UserId}", userId);
        var json = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(
            $"https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users/{userId}", cancellationToken);
        return json;
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("List all posts by a specific user.")]
    public async Task<string> GetUserPosts(
        [Description("The user ID whose posts to retrieve")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching posts for user {UserId}", userId);
        var json = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(
            $"https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts?userId={userId}", cancellationToken);
        return json;
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Create a new post for a user.")]
    public async Task<string> CreatePost(
        [Description("The user ID authoring the post")] int userId,
        [Description("Post title")] string title,
        [Description("Post body content")] string body,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Creating post for user {UserId}", userId);
        var payload = new { userId, title, body };
        var response = await httpClient.PostAsJsonAsync(
            "https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts", payload, cancellationToken);
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

### `Program.cs` — stdio transport

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: route all logging to stderr so stdout stays clean for JSON-RPC
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient();  // registers IHttpClientFactory + HttpClient

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();      // auto-discovers [McpServerToolType] classes

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

### How DI works for MCP tools

The SDK hooks into the standard `Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection` container. There are two injection styles:

**1. Constructor injection (non-static class, shown above)**
`ApiTools` is a non-static class with a primary constructor taking `HttpClient` and `ILogger<ApiTools>`. The SDK creates an instance per tool call, resolving dependencies from the DI container. You register services in `Program.cs` (`AddHttpClient()`, etc.) and the SDK does the rest.

**2. Method parameter injection (static class)**
For stateless tools, you can use a `static` class and accept DI services directly as method parameters:

```csharp
[McpServerToolType]
public static class SimpleTools
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Ping the API.")]
    public static async Task<string> Ping(
        HttpClient httpClient,               // injected by DI — hidden from schema
        [Description("Endpoint path")] string path,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        return await httpClient.GetStringAsync(path, cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

**Key rule:** Parameters with `[Description]` appear in the tool schema (visible to the LLM). Parameters that are DI-registered types (`HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, `CancellationToken`, `IMcpServer`, `IProgress<>`) are **automatically injected** and hidden from the schema. No extra configuration needed — the SDK tells them apart by type.
